> Is there a case where we care to query based on r.subject = 'team1'?

@tysonnorris Current query is design to match to current [subject view][1]

```js
function (doc) {
  if(doc.uuid && doc.key && !doc.blocked) {
    var v = {namespace: doc.subject, uuid: doc.uuid, key: doc.key};
    emit([doc.subject], v);
    emit([doc.uuid, doc.key], v);
  }
  if(doc.namespaces && !doc.blocked) {
    doc.namespaces.forEach(function(namespace) {
      var v = {_id: namespace.name + '/limits', namespace: namespace.name, uuid: namespace.uuid, key: namespace.key};
      emit([namespace.name], v);
      emit([namespace.uuid, namespace.key], v);
    });
  }
}
```
From what I understand initially the key, uuid and name were at top level in a subject doc i.e. only one namespace per subject was there. Later design evolved to support multiple namespace per subject.

So the or clause is more for compatibility purpose

[1]: https://github.com/apache/incubator-openwhisk/blob/master/ansible/files/auth_index.json

My real question is : if multiple records are returned, is it guaranteed to
be safe to choose the first one? If this query is used for credentials
lookup, and the credentials are in the second record they won’t be found -
is that ok?

(This would be moot if the single record was returned by comparing only the
nested field instead of the top level field)

